<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06061178 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06061178 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Noriega  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  AUTO; ACCIDENT; DEATH; PANAMA; LEADER; DRUG; TRIAL; US  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A key government witness who linked Manuel Noriega and two co-defendants to ashipment of cocaine died in a car crash before he had a chance to testify,officials said Thursday.;    Ramon Navarro, a confessed drug dealer to whomthe government gave $170,000 and immunity in exchange for his cooperation,died when his car left the road and smashed into an electrical transformerWednesday night, said Metro-Dade police spokesman Ralph Fernandez.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WITNESS IN NORIEGA DRUG CASE DIESCRASH KILLS DEALER BEFORE TESTIMONY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;We have no indication of foul play, but the investigation is continuing,&quot;he said. Blood-alcohol tests are expected to be available Friday, Fernandezsaid.;    Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Mueller said his office would &quot;lookinto the circumstances&quot; of Navarro's death to determine whether it was anaccident.;    Police searched the neighborhood after Navarro's red BMW crashedand told two residents the car's passenger door was found open and a gun wason the front seat.;    Police told the residents, who spoke to the AssociatedPress on condition of anonymity, that Navarro was traveling 70 to 75 mph alonga straight stretch of road when he apparently was cut off by another car thatmay have come from a side street.;    One of the neighbors reported hearing asecond car just before the accident.;    The trial of Noriega's twoco-defendants, William Saldarriaga and Brian Davidow, began Wednesday. Theirattorneys Thursday asked for time to consider mistrial motions.;    U.S.District Judge William Hoeveler declined to halt the proceedings anddownplayed the possibility he would grant a mistrial.;    &quot;If it's a bona fideaccident, it shouldn't prejudice anyone,&quot; said Hoeveler. The judge denied adefense request for a mistrial.;    Outside the courtroom, lead prosecutorMichael Sullivan said Navarro's death would not interrupt the prosecution.;   &quot;We're going straight ahead -- damn the torpedoes,&quot; Sullivan said.;   Saldarriaga, 44 and Davidow, 29, are accused of conspiring with Noriega toship over 700 pounds of cocaine aboard the luxury yacht Krill. Noriega is tobe tried separately in June.;    Navarro was expected to testify in the nextfew days. His testimony before a grand jury helped indict all three men.;   &quot;The Krill was his deal, he brought the case to the grand jury, and he was themain witness against my client,&quot; said Richard Sharpstein, Davidow's attorney.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Miami  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910301  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  377  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 1, 199100061178,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>